   <titles>
      <title>The Inversion Transformation</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The inversion transformation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> is given by</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>T\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[n],\quad T(\Vect{x}) := (-1)\cdot\Vect{x}</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>Why is it called ‘inversion transformation’? – <math>
                     <latex>T</latex>
                  </math> is called inversion transformation because it inverts each vector. The effect of this transformation on objects is also described as ‘reflection about the origin’.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media xmlns="Theorem" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img xmlns="" src="ims/Inversion.png"/>
            </media>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>To find the matrix representing <math>
                     <latex>T</latex>
                  </math>, we note that <math>
                     <latex>T</latex>
                  </math> transforms the basic vector <math>
                     <latex>\StdBss{j}</latex>
                  </math> into
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <term>of a contraction</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The matrix representing the contraction of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                           </math> with factor <math>
                              <latex> 0 &lt; s &lt; 1 </latex>
                           </math> is represented by the matrix <math>
                              <latex>s\cdot \IdMtrx[n]</latex>
                           </math>; i.e. <math>
                              <latex>s</latex>
                           </math> times the identity matrix of size <math>
                              <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>contraction</term>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The matrix representing the contraction of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                           </math> with factor <math>
                              <latex> 0 &lt; s &lt; 1 </latex>
                           </math> is represented by the matrix <math>
                              <latex>s\cdot \IdMtrx[n]</latex>
                           </math>; i.e. <math>
                              <latex>s</latex>
                           </math> times the identity matrix of size <math>
                              <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>T(\StdBss{j}) = - \StdBss{j} = (0,\dots ,0,-1,0,\dots ,0)</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>Therefore <math>
                     <latex>T</latex>
                  </math> is represented by the matrix of size <math>
                     <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
s\cdot \IdMtrx[n] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp;             &amp; 0 \\
\vdots &amp; &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right]
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>For example, the inversion of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> in the picture above is</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
T\from \RNr[2] \longrightarrow \RNr[2],\qquad D(x,y) = (-x,-y) = 
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
-1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right] \left[ \begin{array}{c} x \\ y \end{array} \right]
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
